content.explanation:
Cylindrical = polar + height. A point is (r, θ, z):
- r = distance from the center axis (like polar)
- θ = angle around the axis (like polar)
- z = height up or down {{viz:diagram-02}}

Imagine standing on the floor looking down at a target. Polar (r, θ) tells you where on the floor. Add z and you know the height—maybe the target is on a shelf above! {{viz:anim-01}}

**Best for:** Anything cylindrical or with circular symmetry. Spinning tops, water vortexes, engines, pipes. {{viz:chart-01}}

Cartesian (x, y, z) and cylindrical both describe 3D space. Cylindrical is just better when something has circular symmetry around an axis.

The axis is usually vertical (z), and you measure angle and distance around it. Like radar with altitude!
